---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout
    title="Chart Redesign & Critique Clinic | tcplot: Data Visualization in Minneapolis and St. Paul"
    description="Bring a genuinely bad chart from the wild and the room workshops fixes live."
>
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-8">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto mt-8 mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">
                Upcoming: A Chart Redesign &amp; Critique Clinic
            </h2>

            <div class="mb-6 text-gray-700">
                <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">
                    Saturday, Aug 29 · 10:00 AM to 12:00 PM CDT
                </p>
                <p class="flex items-start gap-2 mt-1">
                    <svg
                        class="w-5 h-5 mt-0.5 shrink-0 text-gray-400"
                        viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                        fill="currentColor"
                        aria-hidden="true"
                    >
                        <path
                            fill-rule="evenodd"
                            d="M12 2c-3.866 0-7 3.07-7 6.857 0 4.34 4.686 9.86 6.412 11.74a.8.8 0 0 0 1.176 0C14.314 18.717 19 13.197 19 8.857 19 5.07 15.866 2 12 2Zm0 9.5a2.5 2.5 0 1 1 0-5 2.5 2.5 0 0 1 0 5Z"
                            clip-rule="evenodd"></path>
                    </svg>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >The Coffee Shop NE</span
                        ><br />2852 Johnson St NE · Minneapolis, MN</span
                    >
                </p>
            </div>

            <p class="text-xl text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                Bring the worst chart you've seen this year.
            </p>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                We've all seen them — the dual-axis monstrosity, the 3D exploding
                pie, the bar chart with a truncated baseline that quietly lies.
                Bring a genuinely bad chart you found in the wild, and the room
                will workshop fixes live. Together we'll diagnose what's broken
                and redesign it on the spot.
            </p>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                It turns out the fastest way to get better at making charts is to
                take apart someone else's. Every bad chart is a small mystery:
                what was it trying to say, and where did it lose the plot?
            </p>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                How it works
            </h3>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-gray-600 mb-8">
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        >Bring a bad chart — a screenshot, a photo, a printout,
                        or a link.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        >Give it a 60-second intro: where you found it and what
                        it's trying to say.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        >The room diagnoses — what's misleading, confusing, or
                        just plain ugly.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        >We redesign live — on the whiteboard, on paper, or in
                        your tool of choice.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        >Repeat with as many charts as we have time for.</span
                    >
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                What makes a great "bad chart"
            </h3>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-gray-600 mb-8">
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        >From the wild — a news story, a slide deck, a dashboard,
                        a product, a cereal box.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        >It's trying to make a real point but trips over itself
                        getting there.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        >Ideally not a coworker's work — unless you're feeling
                        brave and they're not in the room.</span
                    >
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                What you'll leave with
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                A sharper eye for the traps in your own charts, a working toolkit
                of fixes, and — if it was yours — a redesign of the very chart
                you walked in with.
            </p>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                Ground rules
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                We critique the chart, not the person who made it. Curiosity over
                dunking. The goal is better charts, not worse feelings.
            </p>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                Who this is for
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                Anyone who makes or reads charts — D3, Tableau, ggplot2,
                Observable, spreadsheets, or none of the above. All tools and
                skill levels welcome.
            </p>

            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
                Hope to see you there!
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</Layout>
